Tullus (accord- ing to Florus) omnem militarem disciplinam artemque bellandi condidit: Cicero attributes to him the institution of the fetial law, but Livy divides that honour, ascribing the formalities of foedera to Tullus HostiliuS, and of the declaration of war (res repetere) to Ancus Marcius. Tullus destroyed Alba, and gave the Albans a home on the Caelian mount, 3ηεί their chiefs a share in the state, the Senate, and the army. Ancus settled Latins from Politorium, Tellenae‚ and Ficana on the Aventine, and others near the shrine of Murcia, to connect the Palatine and the Aventine. Tullus built a new curia, called after him Hostilia (and it is quite probable that the building did belong to the regal period), to accommodate the enlarged Senate: Ancus built the prison hard by, called in later times carcer Mamertinus ¹. 1t was he, moreover‚ who occupied and fortified the Ianiculum, constructing the pons sublicius to connect it with the city: and it was he who dug the Quiritium fossa to improve the defences of Rome at the weaker points, His defensive scheme was completed by the seizure of the silva Mesia from the Veientines, and by the occupation of Ostia.

In this record three points of importance stand out—the destruction os Alba, the fortification of the Janiculum‚ and the foundation of Ostia. There is no reason to doubt the destruction of Alba: but it is scarcely probable that there was a complete or wholesale transference of the Albans to Rome itself. The records of the close association of Bovillae, a town as ancient as it is historically insignificant, with the Feriae Latinae contain evidence which at any rate suggests that some of the evicted Albans may have found a home there.
